description:
For many years most of Alan Moore's Captain Britain work has been out of print and not fully collected.  Part of the reason was Alan Moore legally blocking the reprints for so long.  This legal block put a strain to the relationship of Alan Moore and Alan Davis.  Both gentlemen have been long time friends, until the friction of the reprints became an issue.  Moore being proud to stick to his values swore never to work with Marvel again, thus refusing them reprint rights.  Alan Davis was effected as well without the reprints means now royalty residuals.
 
In 2009 the complete acclaimed run of Alan Moore and Alan Davis was collected in the Captain Britain Omnibus.  This Omnibus also collects stories from Jamie Delano who has a habit of taking out previous Moore work, such as D.R. and Quinch and Hellblazer, which is the spin-off to Moore's Swamp Thing.
name: Captain Britain Omnibus

description:
Kazuya was a teenager who was always looking for love in all the wrong places - and with all the wrong techniques. He was head-over-heels for Mayumi, but could never work up the nerve to talk to her. Jun, meanwhile, was hot for Kazuya - a fact that did not sit well with Jun’s boyfriend. His real troubles, however, started when he made the mistake of ogling Yuki, a pretty girl he met at the marketplace. Yuki decked him, then reported the incident to her mother, a witch.

Before Kazuya knew what hit him, the witch had cast a “helter-skelter” spell which caused Kazuya to periodically turn into a little boy. Unfortunately, the spell also caught an innocent flower seller, causing her to turn into a little girl. Unless Kazuya can find and kiss his one true love, the spell will never be broken; if he doesn’t do it soon, demons will come for his soul!

In 1948 the title was brought back with issue 1 this time featuring Marvel's new "working girls," strips such as Tessie the Typist, Nellie the Nurse and Millie the Model.

For a time with the addision of this title Millie the Model would be outdoing Captain Ameria and the Human Torch who were by then down to only 1 title each while Millie was staring in 3 or 4 with more to come in the 50's.

description: In the 1950s British publisher L. Miller and Son held a license to reprint Fawcett's Captain Marvel and his related titles in the U.K., and were publishing Captain Marvel and Captain Marvel Jr. However, in 1953, after a punishing legal battle with DC Comics over claims that Captain Marvel infringed DC's Superman copyrights, Fawcett ceased publication and decided not to renew L. Miller's license. Since Captain Marvel and Captain Marvel Jr. were two of their more popular titles, Len Miller enlisted the assistance of artist and writer Mick Anglo to come up with a rescue plan. He created new characters, Marvelman, Young Marvelman and Kid Marvelman to replace Captain Marvel, Captain Marvel Jr. and Mary Marvel respectively, and, with #25, cover dated 3rd February 1954, L. Miller's two reprint titles were renamed Marvelman and Young Marvelman and began publishing stories produced by Mick Anglo's studio. Both were highly successful, and ran until #370 in February 1963, although towards the end, after Mick Anglo left the titles, they began reprinting old stories. There were also nine Marvelman Annuals.
name: Marvelman
